snippet.title: The Amber Guyger murder trial: Day 1
snippet.description:
Former Dallas police officer Amber Guyger is on trial for murder after she fatally shot Botham Shem Jean on September 6, 2018.  

Guyger was off duty but still in uniform when she went into Jean's apartment at South Side Flats. She told investigators she believed she was walking into her own apartment and shot Jean believing he was an intruder.

snippet.title: Johnny Depp, Amber Heard arrive at UK High Court for libel trial
snippet.description:
(20 Jul 2020) JOHNNY DEPP, AMBER HEARD ARRIVE AT UK HIGH COURT FOR LIBEL TRIAL
Johnny Depp and Amber Heard arrived at Britain's High Court Monday (20 JULY 2020) for the final week's proceedings in Depp's libel suit against a British tabloid that accused him of assaulting his former spouse.
After a week and a half of testimony from Depp and several current or former employees of Depp and Heard, Heard is due to give her side of the story as she enters the witness box.
Heard alleges Depp was violent towards her on 14 occasions between 2013 and 2016, in settings including Depp's private island in the Bahamas, a rented house in Australia and the couple's downtown Los Angeles penthouse.
Depp denies the allegations and claims Heard was the aggressor during their volatile relationship, which he has likened to “a crime scene waiting to happen.”
Depp is suing News Group Newspapers, publisher of The Sun, and the paper’s executive editor, Dan Wootton, over an April 2018 article that called him a “wife-beater.” He strongly denies abusing Heard.
Depp, 57, and Heard, 34, met on the set of the 2011 comedy “The Rum Diary” and married in Los Angeles in February 2015. Heard filed for divorce the following year, and the divorce was finalized in 2017.

snippet.title: Day 15: Amber Heard arrives at High Court as Johnny Depp trial draws to a close
snippet.description:
The Hollywood star smiled and waved at fans as she arrived at London's Royal Courts of Justice this morning for the culmination of a court battle that has revealed lurid details about her relationship with former husband Johnny Depp. Depp is suing News Group Newspapers (NGN), publisher of The Sun, and its executive editor Dan Wootton over a 2018 article which labelled him a 'wife beater'. Lawyers for the tabloid's publisher will be making closing submissions today, before Mr Depp's lawyers make their closing submissions on Tuesday. Summing up for The Sun, lawyer Sasha Wass said the newspaper's defence 'is one of truth - namely that Mr. Depp did indeed beat his wife.' Wass said there was 'overwhelming evidence of domestic violence or wife-beating behavior, cataloged over a three-year period.'

snippet.title: Johnny Depp says Amber Heard withheld his rehab medicine
snippet.description: Johnny Depp has accused Amber Heard of withholding his rehab medicine in 2014 during a trip to his private island.  During the third day of his libel trial in London, the actor told the court how he "sobbed like a child" during the alleged incident.  In a witness statement, the Pirates of the Caribbean actor claimed Heard "often intervened and withheld medicine from me" during a trip to his Bahamas island.  Depp added it was "one of the cruellest things that she has ever done".  The star went to claim he was left "sobbing like a child on the floor" and would suffer the "heebie-jeebies" and have stomach cramps.  Read More Related Articles  Read More Related Articles   Speaking in court, Sasha Wass QC, barrister for News Group Newspapers, said Depp and Heard stayed on one side of his island while his nurse had accommodation on the other side.  Using text messages as evidence, the QC said: "All the way through this document it is clear that Ms Heard is the one maintaining contact with Debbie Lloyd and is effectively looking after you.  "She was effectively dedicating herself to your wellbeing during this detoxification, wasn't she?"   Read More Related Articles    After Depp confirmed "Yes, she was trying to help me," the QC continued suggesting that Ms Heard was "effectively acting as your nurse".  Depp replied: "She was in control of the meds, she was in control of when I was taking the meds, she would give me the time to take the meds."  Wass continued: "I am going to suggest you lied about the extent of her drugs use and alcohol consumption in order to discredit her in this court hearing."   Read More Related Articles    After the actor said: "No." the QC continued: "She was doing what she was being told to do by the experts."  Depp went on to state be 'didn't know that she explicitly followed the orders of the registered nurse to the letter."  The trial is expected to last for three weeks

snippet.title: Depp, Heard arrive for second day of UK libel trial
snippet.description:
(8 Jul 2020) Actor Johnny Depp and his ex-wife, actress Amber Heard arrived at the High Court in London on Wednesday for the second day of a three-week trial over his libel case against a British newspaper.
Depp is suing British tabloid The Sun over an April 2018 story headlined “Potty - How can JK Rowling be ‘genuinely happy’ casting wife beater Johnny Depp in the new Fantastic Beasts film?” 
The newspaper's lawyers plan to use Heard's allegations of abuse by Depp to defend the “wife beater” claim.
The trial over his libel claims opened Tuesday. 
It is one of the first major cases to be held in person since Britain began to lift its coronavirus lockdown.
Depp, 57, and Heard, 34, met on the set of the 2011 comedy “The Rum Diary” and married in Los Angeles in February 2015. They divorced in 2017, and now bitterly accuse one another of abuse.
While Heard isn't on trial, the case is also a showdown between the former spouses, who accuse each other of being controlling, violent and deceitful.
 It is set to put the two performers’ complex private lives under a microscope.
Depp is also suing Heard in the United States for 50 million US dollars for allegedly defaming him in a Washington Post article about domestic abuse. 
That case is due to be heard next year.

snippet.title: Witness Says 'NO BRUISES' On Amber Heard As Johnny Depp Trial Continues
snippet.description:

snippet.title: Deppl, Heard arrive for libel trial in London
snippet.description:
(15 Jul 2020) Johnny Depp and ex-wife Amber Heard arrived at Britain's High Court on Wednesday to attend a hearing of Depp's libel claim against a tabloid newspaper that accused him of domestic abuse.
The Hollywood star is suing News Group Newspapers, publisher of The Sun, and the paper's executive editor, Dan Wootton, over an April 2018 article that called him a "wife-beater." 
He strongly denies abusing Heard.
Depp, 57, and Heard, 34, met on the set of the 2011 comedy "The Rum Diary" and married in Los Angeles in February 2015. 
Heard, a model and actress, filed for divorce the following year, and the divorce was finalised in 2017.
Depp has depicted a tumultuous relationship with Heard during a period when he was trying to kick drugs and alcohol, and sometimes lapsing.
He called the relationship "a crime scene waiting to happen." 
But he denied Heard's claims that he slapped, hit, headbutted and threw things at her, and accused his ex-wife of compiling a dossier of fake claims against him as an "insurance policy."

snippet.title: ジョニー・デップ DV疑惑で元妻と泥沼暴露合戦⁉︎ Johnny Depp 俳優 裁判 trial アンバー・ハード Amber Heard 女優 離婚 イギリス ザ・サン セレブ 億万長者 喧嘩
snippet.description:
ジョニー・デップとアンバー・ハードとの離婚劇に、アンバーの元恋人であるイーロン・マスクが巻き込まれてしまったようだ。

わずか1年ほどの結婚生活を経て2016年5月に離婚を申請したアンバーによるDV発言を受け、名誉棄損で訴えを起こしているジョニー。先日、アンバーが「首を絞められたリ、殴られたり、缶や未開封の瓶を投げつけられたりした」など、ジョニーから受けたとする暴力の詳細を説明したことで、ジョニーとの破局後に交際していたイーロンを「虚偽の助けをした友人」として裁判に召喚したという。

ジョニーの弁護団は、アンバーが証拠として提出している動画や音源、写真などについて、イーロンをはじめとしたアンバー側の証人に追及する意向だと説明している。

アンバーの発言を「新たな虚偽」としているジョニー側は、不起訴とはなったものの、アンバーには2009年に元恋人ターシャ・ヴァン・リーに対するドメスティックバイオレンスの疑いでの逮捕歴があることも引き合いに出し、その信頼性について懸念を示している。

一方でアンバーは先日、ジョニーは頻繁に記憶を失くすほど泥酔していたため、自分がはたらいた暴力も覚えていないのだと主張していた。

snippet.title: Fallout from Amber Heard and Johnny Depp trial could cost the pair millions
snippet.description: The fallout from the Johnny Depp and Amber Heard libel trial could cost the stars hundreds of millions of pounds, showbiz experts claim.  Depp was dropped from his £500million role as Captain Jack Sparrow in the sixth Pirates Of The Caribbean movie before the court battle began.  One entertainment industry expert said: "The fallout will spread far and wide and deep – right into these stars' wallets.  "It could cost them hundreds of millions."  Insiders say Depp would lose even more if he is cut adrift from Harry Potter author JK Rowling’s Fantastic Beasts franchise.    Meanwhile, Heard, 34, could lose her role in the planned sequel to the 2018 Aquaman movie.  The film franchise’s producers were said to have a representative in court.  She could also lose her position as a United Nations human rights champion and the face of cosmetic giant L’Oreal.  But the fallout extends beyond the two main protagonists. Depp’s Brit actor pal Paul Bettany, 49, could wave goodbye to his role as the star of the Disney+ mini-series WandaVision after Depp admitted the pair had dabbled in drugs.  Depp, 57, is suing News Group Newspapers Ltd and journalist Dan Wootton over an April 2018 article which branded him a wife beater.  The judge's ruling is expected in September.   Heard gave an impassioned speech on the High Court steps yesterday as the trial drew to a close.  She said: "I travelled here to the UK to testify as a witness to assist the court.  "After getting a restraining order in 2016 and finalising my divorce I just wanted to move on with my life.  "I did not file this lawsuit and despite its significance I would have preferred not to be here in court."   Heard continued: "It has been incredibly painful to relive the break-up of my relationship.  "To have my motives and my truth questioned and the most traumatic and intimate parts of my life with Johnny shared in court and broadcast to the world.  "I stand by my testimony and I now place my faith in British legal system."

snippet.localized.title: Fallout from Amber Heard and Johnny Depp trial could cost the pair millions
snippet.localized.description: The fallout from the Johnny Depp and Amber Heard libel trial could cost the stars hundreds of millions of pounds, showbiz experts claim.  Depp was dropped from his £500million role as Captain Jack Sparrow in the sixth Pirates Of The Caribbean movie before the court battle began.  One entertainment industry expert said: "The fallout will spread far and wide and deep – right into these stars' wallets.  "It could cost them hundreds of millions."  Insiders say Depp would lose even more if he is cut adrift from Harry Potter author JK Rowling’s Fantastic Beasts franchise.    Meanwhile, Heard, 34, could lose her role in the planned sequel to the 2018 Aquaman movie.  The film franchise’s producers were said to have a representative in court.  She could also lose her position as a United Nations human rights champion and the face of cosmetic giant L’Oreal.  But the fallout extends beyond the two main protagonists. Depp’s Brit actor pal Paul Bettany, 49, could wave goodbye to his role as the star of the Disney+ mini-series WandaVision after Depp admitted the pair had dabbled in drugs.  Depp, 57, is suing News Group Newspapers Ltd and journalist Dan Wootton over an April 2018 article which branded him a wife beater.  The judge's ruling is expected in September.   Heard gave an impassioned speech on the High Court steps yesterday as the trial drew to a close.  She said: "I travelled here to the UK to testify as a witness to assist the court.  "After getting a restraining order in 2016 and finalising my divorce I just wanted to move on with my life.  "I did not file this lawsuit and despite its significance I would have preferred not to be here in court."   Heard continued: "It has been incredibly painful to relive the break-up of my relationship.  "To have my motives and my truth questioned and the most traumatic and intimate parts of my life with Johnny shared in court and broadcast to the world.  "I stand by my testimony and I now place my faith in British legal system."
